# 🧠 Where Animate.css is ACTUALLY used in real projects

## ✅ 1. Page Load / Section Entry Animations

👉 Most common real-world use

Example:

- Hero text fades in
- Cards slide up on load

```jsx
<h1 className="animate__animated animate__fadeInUp">Welcome</h1>
```

✔ Runs once → perfect
✔ No interaction needed

---

## ✅ 2. Scroll-based Reveal (Very Common)

👉 Used in landing pages

- Sections appear while scrolling
- Features fade/slide into view

Used with:

- `IntersectionObserver`

✔ Looks modern
✔ Lightweight

---

## ✅ 3. Alerts / Feedback (Small UI moments)

👉 Quick feedback animations

- Error → `shakeX`
- Success → `tada`
- Notification → `fadeInDown`

✔ Short, one-time animation
✔ Improves UX

---

## ✅ 4. Modals / Popups

👉 Opening animation only

```jsx
<div className="animate__animated animate__zoomIn">Modal Content</div>
```

✔ Entry/exit animation
✔ No complex interaction

---

## ✅ 5. Simple CTA Highlight

👉 Example:

- “Buy Now” button → `pulse`

```jsx
<button className="animate__animated animate__pulse animate__infinite">
  Buy Now
</button>
```

✔ Draws attention
⚠️ Use carefully (not everywhere)

---

# ❌ Where NOT to use Animate.css

## 🚫 1. Hover Effects

👉 Doesn’t re-trigger smoothly

❌ Bad:

- Button hover grow/shrink

👉 Use instead:
**Framer Motion**

---

## 🚫 2. Complex UI Animations

- Dropdown animations
- Page transitions
- Drag interactions

👉 Animate.css can’t handle logic

---

## 🚫 3. Continuous Interactive UI

- Toggle switches
- Sliders
- Dynamic components

👉 Needs JS-based animation

---

# 🎯 Real Decision Rule

👉 Ask this:

### ❓ “Is animation one-time or interactive?”

| Type                        | Use              |
| --------------------------- | ---------------- |
| One-time (on load / scroll) | Animate.css ✅   |
| Interactive (hover/click)   | Framer Motion ✅ |

